The Path to Nuclear Disarmament
NEW YORK – Weapons of mass destruction and disarmament represent one of the most difficult challenges the world is currently facing. One of my priorities as Secretary-General of the United Nations is to promote the global common good and find solutions to problems that know no borders.
A world without nuclear weapons is a common good of highest importance.
My interest in this topic is partly based on personal experiences.
My home country, South Korea, has suffered under the devastation of conventional warfare and has been exposed to the threat of nuclear weapons and other weapons of mass destruction.
Yet such threat scenarios obviously exist not only in Asia.
Although the use of nuclear weapons has long been regarded as taboo, disarmament remains merely an aspiration.
Is a taboo that merely refers to the use of such weapons even sufficient?
When it comes to nuclear weapons, individual states make the most important decisions.
Yet the UN plays a decisive role in this.
We offer a central forum in which states can agree on norms that serve their common interests.
We analyze and inform in order to achieve our agreed goals, and we advocate for them.
Most states have decided to forgo nuclear weapons and have consolidated their commitments under the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty.
Yet some states view such weapons as a status symbol, and others see them as the ultimate deterrent against an attack with nuclear weapons, which primarily explains the estimated 26,000 weapons that still exist.
Unfortunately, the doctrine of nuclear deterrence is contagious, making non-proliferation more difficult and giving rise to new risks that nuclear weapons will be used.
The world remains concerned about nuclear activities in North Korea and Iran, and there is broad support for efforts to address these concerns through peaceful means.
There are also concerns that we may be facing a "nuclear renaissance," as nuclear energy is seen as a clean energy alternative in times of increasing efforts to combat climate change.
The main concern is that this will lead to the production and use of more nuclear material that must be protected from proliferation and terrorist threats.
The obstacles to disarmament are enormous.
Yet the costs and risks of their alternatives never receive the attention they deserve.
Let us consider the enormous opportunity costs of high military budgets.
According to the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute (Stockholm Institute for International Peace Research), military spending rose last year to over $1.3 trillion.
Ten years ago, the Brookings Institution published a study estimating the total costs of nuclear weapons in the United States alone at over $5.8 trillion, including future cleanup costs.
That is, by any definition, a huge investment that could have been used for many other productive purposes.
Concerns about the costs of nuclear weapons and the inherent dangers they pose have sparked a global idea of how nuclear disarmament could be revitalized.
We have witnessed the UN Disarmament Commission under Hans Blix, the New Agenda Coalition, and Norway's Seven Nation Initiative.
Australia and Japan established the International Commission on Nuclear Non-Proliferation and Disarmament.
Citizens' groups and nuclear-armed states have also proposed recommendations, such as the Hoover Plan, introduced by Henry Kissinger.
I would like to propose my own Five-Point Plan.
First: I call on all members of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, particularly the nuclear-armed states, to fulfill their obligations under the treaty and to initiate negotiations on effective measures that lead to nuclear disarmament.
They could agree on a framework agreement for separate, mutually reinforcing instruments.
Or they could negotiate a nuclear weapons convention supported by a strong control system, as has long been proposed by the UN.
I have sent a draft of such a convention to all UN members, which provides a good starting point.
The nuclear-armed states should actively engage with other countries on this issue at the UN Conference on Disarmament in Geneva, the only multilateral negotiation forum for disarmament in the world.
The world would also welcome a resumption of bilateral negotiations between the United States and Russia with the aim of substantially and verifiably reducing their arsenals.
Governments should also invest more in control research and development.
The UK's proposal to hold a conference of nuclear-armed states on the topic of control is a concrete step in the right direction.
Second: The permanent members of the Security Council should start discussing security issues in the process of nuclear disarmament.
They could clearly make it evident to the states that do not possess nuclear weapons that they will not be victims of a nuclear attack or the threat thereof.
The Council could also call a summit on nuclear disarmament.
States that are not members of the Non-Proliferation Treaty should halt their nuclear weapon programs and undertake their own disarmament commitments.
Thirdly: Unilateral moratoriums on nuclear tests and the production of fissile materials should be allowed only to a limited extent.
We need new efforts to bring the CTBT into force, as well as momentum to ensure that the Disarmament Conference immediately and without preconditions begins negotiations on a treaty on fissile materials.
I support the establishment of nuclear-weapon-free zones in Central Asia and Africa and strongly endorse efforts to establish such zones in the Middle East.
In addition, I urgently call on all members of the Non-Proliferation Treaty to conclude their security agreements with the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and voluntarily implement the stricter security clauses of the Additional Protocol.
Fourthly: Nuclear-armed states often circulate descriptions of what they do to achieve these goals.
Yet these reports rarely reach the public.
I would like to ask the nuclear-armed states to send such materials to the UN Secretariat and contribute to their further dissemination.
The fact that there is no significant estimate of the total number of nuclear weapons confirms the need for greater transparency.
And finally, various complementary measures are required.
This includes the elimination of other types of mass destruction weapons, new efforts against terrorism with mass destruction weapons, a limitation of the production and trade of conventional weapons, and new weapon bans, among others for rockets and space weapons.
If there are real, confirmed progress in disarmament, the ability to eliminate the nuclear threat will grow exponentially.
By gradually eliminating the deadliest weapons of the world and their components, we make it more difficult to carry out terrorist attacks using weapons of mass destruction.
These proposals offer a new beginning, not only for disarmament, but also for strengthening our system of international peace and international security.
